  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a global issue with varying legal approaches across different countries. Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Anti-Money Laundering (AML) framework\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Stringent reporting requirements\n- Aggressive prosecution strategies\n- Focus on financial institution compliance\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified regulatory approach through EU directives\n- Emphasis on customer due diligence\n- Centralized financial intelligence units\n- Harmonized legal standards across member states\n- Stronger emphasis on preventative measures\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Robust regulatory framework\n- Advanced investigative techniques\n- Strong international cooperation\n- Sophisticated financial monitoring systems\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically more lenient regulations\n- Strict banking secrecy laws\n- Gradual improvements in transparency\n- Increasing international compliance pressures\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict government oversight\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- Emphasis on state control of financial systems\n\n6. Russia\n- Developing legal framework\n- Inconsistent enforcement\n- Complex regulatory environment\n- Limited international transparency\n\nThese approaches reflect different legal, cultural, and economic contexts.",
